#SENDER

import socket
PORT = 7000
sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_DGRAM)
# 🔥 Enable broadcast
sock.setsockopt(socket.SOL_SOCKET, socket.SO_BROADCAST, 1)

message = "Hello Group Communication"

sock.sendto(message.encode(), ('<broadcast>', PORT))

print("Message sent to all receivers")



#RECEIVER
import socket

PORT = 7000

sock = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_DGRAM)

# 🔥 Allow multiple receivers on same port
sock.setsockopt(socket.SOL_SOCKET, socket.SO_REUSEADDR, 1)

sock.bind(('', PORT))

print("Waiting for broadcast...")

while True:
    data, addr = sock.recvfrom(1024)
    print("Received:", data.decode())




RUN--> 
TERMINAL 1-> py receiver.py
TERMINAL 2-> py receiver.py
TERMINAL 3-> py sender.py




Definition
Group communication is a communication method where a single sender transmits data to multiple receivers simultaneously.

🔸 Concept
In this implementation, group communication is achieved using UDP broadcast, where:

Sender sends data to a broadcast address
All receivers listening on the same port receive the message



🔸 Working
Sender creates a UDP socket
Broadcast option is enabled
Message is sent to broadcast address (<broadcast>)
All receivers bound to the same port receive the message
Receivers display the received data

🔸 Features
One-to-many communication
Connectionless (UDP)
Fast and efficient
No need to maintain connections

🔸 Advantages
✔ Simple implementation
✔ Works without internet (LAN/local system)
✔ Supports multiple receivers
✔ No complex configuration

🔸 Disadvantages
❌ No reliability (UDP)
❌ No guarantee of delivery
❌ Can cause network congestion

🔸 Applications
Chat applications
Online multiplayer systems
Notification systems
Distributed systems


👉 “In broadcast communication, a single message is delivered to all devices in the network segment listening on the specified port.”
